sitting usually around 30k a day at the moment.

3
00:00:08,559 --> 00:00:18,720
How does this guy make a million dollars a month when he has hundreds of competitors in a saturated market and a lot of that growth is due to something I call the purple how strategy.

4
00:00:18,720 --> 00:00:24,000
Lane is a software engineer who decided to start a side project called boot.dev.

5
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:30,160
He started to make a little money until one day he came across a marketing channel that would explode his business.

6
00:00:30,160 --> 00:00:35,520
The big shift was going from just blogging to starting with.

7
00:00:35,520 --> 00:00:42,879
I sat down with Lane for a couple hours to learn about his story and figure out what it really takes to build an 8 figureure business as a developer.

8
00:00:42,879 --> 00:00:49,760
And good news is he shared everything including why you should never copy someone else's business idea,

9
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:58,960
what most people get wrong about MVPs, and a full breakdown of his revenue costs and everything you want to know about his million-doll per month business.

10
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:00,800
Now, let's get into it.

11
00:01:00,800 --> 00:01:03,840
I'm Pat Walls and this is Starter Story.

12
00:01:03,840 --> 00:01:05,439
All right, welcome Lane.

13
00:01:05,439 --> 00:01:06,479
Welcome to the channel.

14
00:01:06,479 --> 00:01:09,520
Tell me a little about who you are and what you built.

15
00:01:09,520 --> 00:01:10,799
Yeah, my name is Lane Wagner.

16
00:01:10,799 --> 00:01:12,000
I'm the founder of boot.dev.

17
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,479
It's an online learning platform for software engineers and it's very interactive.

18
00:01:16,479 --> 00:01:19,439
That's kind of the defining unique trait of it.

19
00:01:19,439 --> 00:01:26,080
Really, we're just trying to get you doing as close to what you would be doing in the real world as a software engineer.

20
00:01:26,080 --> 00:01:33,040
So, we're trying to like unsandbox the experience and have you go through the courses like you would in the real world.

21
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:36,720
And we're making almost a million dollars a month at the moment.

22
00:01:36,720 --> 00:01:40,079
Can you give me a further breakdown of how this works as a business?

23
00:01:40,079 --> 00:01:41,600
What's the business model here?

24
00:01:41,600 --> 00:01:47,920
So, it's a coding first platform where you write a ton of code both on your local machine and in the browser.

25
00:01:47,920 --> 00:01:50,159
And all of our content is free.

26
00:01:50,159 --> 00:01:56,240
There's about 30 courses, but you lose interactivity after a certain point if you're not a paying member.

27
00:01:56,240 --> 00:02:02,640
And we're currently sitting at 25,332 active paying members.

28
00:02:02,640 --> 00:02:05,840
You built this website to almost a million dollars a month.

29
00:02:05,840 --> 00:02:08,640
There's a lot of coding courses and a lot of stuff out there.

30
00:02:08,640 --> 00:02:10,319
What did you do differently?

31
00:02:10,319 --> 00:02:12,879
What is your secret ingredient for this business?

32
00:02:12,879 --> 00:02:19,120
In this market, online learning, you've got to differentiate pretty hard because there's a lot of competition in the space.

33
00:02:19,120 --> 00:02:24,720
We kind of had different differentiators along the way as we grew the business over the last four years.

34
00:02:24,720 --> 00:02:26,640
The first was a content differentiation.

35
00:02:26,640 --> 00:02:35,680
So, we're serving this market of people that want to learn back-end technologies and just aren't finding the resources because front-end is so dominant in the online learning space.

36
00:02:35,680 --> 00:02:40,480
The next differentiator was you should make your thing feel totally different, totally unique.

37
00:02:40,480 --> 00:02:43,680
And I I really was inspired by Seth Goden's book, The Purple Cow.

38
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:44,959
Fantastic marketing book.

39
00:02:44,959 --> 00:02:52,720
But the basic idea is when someone lands on your site, as a new entrepreneur, it can be really tempting to go look at a bunch of competitors websites and like,

40
00:02:52,720 --> 00:02:53,920
"Oh man, they're so beautiful.

41
00:02:53,920 --> 00:02:54,800
They're so well-designed.

42
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:56,879
I should make my website look like theirs."

43
00:02:56,879 --> 00:02:57,519
Absolutely.

44
00:02:57,519 --> 00:02:58,879
You should not do that.

45
00:02:58,879 --> 00:02:59,760
Let's go back.

46
00:02:59,760 --> 00:03:08,560
Let's uh if you can give me a little bit of a timeline of what it looked like uh how you came up with the idea for this and you know what were you were doing before you were running this huge business.

47
00:03:08,560 --> 00:03:08,720
Yeah.

48
00:03:08,720 --> 00:03:15,360
