66
00:04:06,560 --> 00:04:15,200
It was 330K, but it gave me enough of like assurance that okay, we could at least have a couple years of runway to try this new business.

67
00:04:15,200 --> 00:04:16,959
Okay, let's talk about ideas.

68
00:04:16,959 --> 00:04:18,320
How did you find this idea?

69
00:04:18,320 --> 00:04:18,639
Yeah.

70
00:04:18,639 --> 00:04:25,120
So, I was a back-end engineering manager and the impetus for the whole thing was I was trying to hire Go developers.

71
00:04:25,120 --> 00:04:26,320
This is back in 2020.

72
00:04:26,320 --> 00:04:27,280
I was having a hard time.

73
00:04:27,280 --> 00:04:32,720
Like, I'd open up, you know, a job position and I'd get like five, six, seven people applying for the job.

74
00:04:32,720 --> 00:04:41,440
And so, it really just seemed to be that people getting into coding were gravitating towards the front end side and almost being pushed to the frontend side by online learning platforms.

75
00:04:41,440 --> 00:04:45,759
So it just seemed to me like there's this huge vacuum in the market where if you wanted to learn back-end stuff,

76
00:04:45,759 --> 00:04:50,479
you want to learn databases, infrastructure, it's very hard to do it online.

77
00:04:50,479 --> 00:04:52,000
All right, let's talk about building.

78
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:55,520
As a developer, how did you take this idea from 0 to one?

79
00:04:55,520 --> 00:05:02,880
So you should have a very good idea of who you're building for and what problem you're solving and you should just solve that problem,

80
00:05:02,880 --> 00:05:07,120
but you should solve it really [ __ ] well because if you don't have a great solution,

81
00:05:07,120 --> 00:05:09,199
you're not going to break into the space.

82
00:05:09,199 --> 00:05:12,080
But you should tightly scope what you're building.

83
00:05:12,080 --> 00:05:14,000
I see this mistake all the time, too.

84
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,360
The idea of just packing on new features, solving different problems.

85
00:05:17,360 --> 00:05:28,800
You should only be listening to what problems your customers have, and then you should be filtering out any problems from customers that aren't exactly the type of customer that you want to serve.

86
00:05:28,800 --> 00:05:36,320
In my opinion, the most dangerous thing you can do is try to serve multiple customer personas.

87
00:05:36,320 --> 00:05:38,639
What's your take on building MVPs?

88
00:05:38,639 --> 00:05:43,960
So I think a lot of people even I mean myself as I launched bootdev think about this incorrectly.

89
00:05:43,960 --> 00:05:48,639
MVP doesn't mean shitty product and it can't mean that.

90
00:05:48,639 --> 00:05:52,320
If it does mean that for you your product is going to flop pretty hard.

91
00:05:52,320 --> 00:05:57,680
You should shoot for minimum quantity not minimum quality.

92
00:05:57,680 --> 00:05:58,000
Okay.

93
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:06,720
So before we get into gross there's one thing that I wanted to ask you cuz I was looking at the notes and I noticed that you use Postthog for analytics the software tool Post Hog.

