00:07:56,240 --> 00:07:57,599
All right, back to the video.

128
00:07:57,599 --> 00:08:00,240
Let's get into how Lane grew this business.

129
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:02,000
Marketing and distribution.

130
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:06,560
Uh, how did you get users to boot.dev and how did you grow this business?

131
00:08:06,560 --> 00:08:11,199
So, from zero to about 2K a month, we really grew from my blog.

132
00:08:11,199 --> 00:08:19,120
It was great for finding people that were really interested in the product and we did a ton of product development over those first year to 12 months.

133
00:08:19,120 --> 00:08:20,400
But then we weren't growing, right?

134
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:27,280
We were like, we started to feel a lot more confident in what we were building, but we we just weren't getting enough people in the door for it to make sense as a business.

135
00:08:27,280 --> 00:08:33,360
And what we quickly found was that trust building, especially in the education space,

136
00:08:33,360 --> 00:08:34,800
is extremely important.

137
00:08:34,800 --> 00:08:40,320
So, working with influencers was like a cheat code because the influencers are already trusted by their audience.

138
00:08:40,320 --> 00:08:49,839
So, if you can get an influencer to try your thing and like it, you kind of unlock a new little section of the market because now their followers will will naturally trust you a lot more.

139
00:08:49,839 --> 00:08:54,800
So then from 10K to 30K, we really grew a lot off the back of these free code camp collabs,

140
00:08:54,800 --> 00:09:04,399
which was basically me recording an 8hour course, giving it to Free Code Camp for free so they can publish on their YouTube channel and us getting some exposure through that.

141
00:09:04,399 --> 00:09:08,240
So going from 30K up to where we're at now, which is almost a million a month.

142
00:09:08,240 --> 00:09:10,399
We had to scale what we were doing.

143
00:09:10,399 --> 00:09:15,120
Like I wasn't going to be able to create all this video content that was going to drive that amount of traffic.

144
00:09:15,120 --> 00:09:19,760
YouTube integrations, YouTube marketing, we've been able to scale that with other creators.

145
00:09:19,760 --> 00:09:26,160
And the unique kind of cheat code that we have as Bootdev is that we have such strong affinity with gaming audience.

146
00:09:26,160 --> 00:09:33,200
So, we've actually done most of our YouTube influencer marketing to gaming audiences rather than coding audiences.

147
00:09:33,200 --> 00:09:33,519
Yeah.

148
00:09:33,519 --> 00:09:41,360
Um, if you had advice for someone to go do their first influencer collab, what would be like a couple bullet points on that?

149
00:09:41,360 --> 00:09:46,240
So, the most important thing is finding the right several influencers to test with.

150
00:09:46,240 --> 00:09:50,560
And the easiest way to find the right ones is to talk to your existing customers.

151
00:09:50,560 --> 00:09:51,680
Hopefully, you have some.

152
00:09:51,680 --> 00:09:53,600
Go ask them who they watch, right?

153
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:54,560
Who they listen to.

154
00:09:54,560 --> 00:09:58,160
This has been the best way for us to source new influencers to work with.

155
00:09:58,160 --> 00:10:05,040
Also, if you're going to work with influencers, there's one giant exploit that you can take advantage of that doesn't work in most other channels,

156
00:10:05,040 --> 00:10:10,160
which is if you're incredibly easy to work with and you do a lot of work for the influencer,

157
00:10:10,160 --> 00:10:11,600
you can get better deals.

158
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:18,480
If you can shoot your own B-roll for the influencer, there's a lot more room for arbitrage when doing one-off deals with influencers.

159
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:22,000
Do everything you can to make their life as easy as possible.

160
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:24,079
Let's talk about product.

161
00:10:24,079 --> 00:10:29,680
We could talk about growth channels all day, but nothing's going to work unless you have a truly great product that people love.

162
00:10:29,680 --> 00:10:31,360
So, tell me what you think about that.

163
00:10:31,360 --> 00:10:35,440
I think the right way to think about where you should be spending your time, whether it's on the product or marketing,

164
00:10:35,440 --> 00:10:41,279
assuming you know you're a small team, is that the product is the thing that really is non-negotiable.

165
00:10:41,279 --> 00:10:48,000
You need the product to be good and you need to have confidence in the product before you spend a lot of time and money marketing the product.

166
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:52,959
There's a minimal amount of marketing you do need to do to get some initial users to get product feedback.

167
00:10:52,959 --> 00:10:56,720
But in that first, you know, pre-product market fit cycle.

168
00:10:56,720 --> 00:11:04,880
All your focus should be on the product and making the product solve the very specific problem for very specific person that you're trying to get it to solve.

169
00:11:04,880 --> 00:11:05,519
That's great.

170
00:11:05,519 --> 00:11:07,760
Let's talk about uh monetization.

171
00:11:07,760 --> 00:11:17,519
Um what I think is cool about your site is that you kind of give away your stuff for free and then you charge a small percentage of people who want that extra feature.

172
00:11:17,519 --> 00:11:23,680
Can you walk through how your business is monetized and what the uh customer journey typically looks like?

173
00:11:23,680 --> 00:11:32,320
It was really kind of an experiment at first of like could we just like make all the content free and you lose interactivity after a certain point if you're not a paying member.

174
00:11:32,320 --> 00:11:40,240
It worked and I think the right business takeaway was let people really understand the product before we ask them to pay for it.

175
00:11:40,240 --> 00:11:41,760
It was resonating enough with them.

176
00:11:41,760 --> 00:11:51,839
So that's again comes back to the like you do need to spend all this time iterating on the product and making sure that you're actually solving the problem and you need to be able to convince people that your

177
00:11:51,839 --> 00:12:01,680
product solves the problem before the purchasing decision happens which just so happens in our case to be a longer free trial or free demo of the interactive features.

178
00:12:01,680 --> 00:12:02,240
Well, that's cool.

179
00:12:02,240 --> 00:12:11,600
And that brings me to my next topic, which is if you could just break down what kind of tools and languages you use to build bootdev and also what tools you use to run the business.

180
00:12:11,600 --> 00:12:14,959
So for the tech nerds out there, it is a fully customuilt web app.

181
00:12:14,959 --> 00:12:18,079
So we use Golang on the back end, Postgress is our database.

182
00:12:18,079 --> 00:12:21,360
We host everything on Google Cloud um and Cloudflare.

183
00:12:21,360 --> 00:12:25,360
We use Kubernetes, Docker, Vue, Nux, JavaScript, TypeScript.

184
00:12:25,360 --> 00:12:28,160
Again, very very custom tech stack.

185
00:12:28,160 --> 00:12:34,639
For the marketing nerds out there, of course, we use Post Hog for all of our product analytics and we use Send Grid for all of our email stuff.

186
00:12:34,639 --> 00:12:39,839
We use their email API and using both together has I mean it eliminates another bill,

187
00:12:39,839 --> 00:12:41,680
but it also just makes integration easier.

188
00:12:41,680 --> 00:12:44,079
And then for the fintech nerds, we're just using Stripe.

189
00:12:44,079 --> 00:12:44,880
Stripe is great.

190
00:12:44,880 --> 00:12:47,760
I can't imagine using anything else at this point.

191
00:12:47,760 --> 00:12:49,680
On that same topic, these tools cost money.

192
00:12:49,680 --> 00:12:53,839
I'd love to get a little bit more details on the actual costs of this business.

193
00:12:53,839 --> 00:12:56,399
Not just the tools, but just the cost as a whole.

194
00:12:56,399 --> 00:12:59,360
What do the costs and margins look like for bootdev?

195
00:12:59,360 --> 00:13:04,720
So our total revenue for 2024 was $5.7 million.

196
00:13:04,720 --> 00:13:08,320
The cost of goods sold on that revenue was only 300k.

197
00:13:08,320 --> 00:13:16,000
So we spent around $6 to $700,000 last year on salaries and like full-time contractors.

198
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:19,200
And then the bulk of our expenses were marketing expenses.

199
00:13:19,200 --> 00:13:28,160
We spent almost $2 million on marketing, leaving us an actual profit at the end of the year of around $2.5 million.

200
00:13:28,160 --> 00:13:28,560
Cool.

